---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, "");
---

<Base
  title="For agents — Otlyra"
  description="Drive Otlyra over WebDriver BiDi, or connect it to an agent as an MCP server. Seven tools, no script engine required."
>
  <h1>Driving it from outside</h1>
  <p class="lede">
    Otlyra answers <a href="https://www.w3.org/TR/webdriver-bidi/">WebDriver BiDi</a>,
    the W3C protocol for driving a browser from another program — and speaks the
    Model Context Protocol for agents, which is the same vocabulary wearing a
    different shape.
  </p>

  <h2>An agent, in one line</h2>
  <pre><code>claude mcp add otlyra -- /path/to/otlyra --mcp</code></pre>
  <table>
    <tr><th>Tool</th><th>What it is for</th></tr>
    <tr><td><code>browser_navigate</code></td><td>Open a page and wait for it to load</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>browser_screenshot</code></td><td>A picture of the page as it is now</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>browser_find</code></td><td>Find elements by CSS selector; returns a handle for each</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>browser_explain</code></td><td>Why an element looks the way it does — computed style, box model, grid tracks</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>browser_highlight</code></td><td>Draw the inspector's overlay, so a screenshot shows which element is meant</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>browser_act</code></td><td>Click, type, scroll</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>browser_timings</code></td><td>How long each stage of the last frame took</td></tr>
  </table>
  <p>
    Seven, and deliberately seven: a tool list is read in full before every
    decision, so one that is rarely the right answer costs something on every turn
    it is not used — which is most of them.
  </p>

  <h3>Two things shaped for an agent rather than a program</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>
      A screenshot comes back as an <strong>image</strong>, not as base64 in a
      string. An agent that can see the page settles questions no amount of JSON
      would.
    </li>
    <li>
      A tool that could not do something answers with a sentence, not a transport
      error. The call reached the browser and the browser answered; an agent can
      read what it said and try something else.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Naming an element instead of a point</h2>
  <pre><code>first = browser.find("#first")[0]
browser.click(first)          # no coordinates anywhere</code></pre>
  <p>
    The centre is resolved against where the engine <em>actually drew</em> the
    element — the same rectangle a real click is tested against. A driver that
    computed the point itself would be keeping a second opinion about the layout,
    and the two would part company the first time anything moved.
  </p>
  <p>
    The selector is matched by the engine's own matcher, the one the cascade
    styles with, so <code>.card</code> finds exactly the elements a stylesheet
    would have hit.
  </p>

  <h2>Why BiDi and not Chrome's protocol</h2>
  <p>
    The obvious answer was the Chrome DevTools Protocol, because that is what most
    tools speak. It does not survive contact:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>CDP is Chromium's private protocol. Firefox dropped it in 129.</li>
    <li>
      Playwright's CDP client is written against Chromium's internals rather than
      against a specification, so answering to the same method names would not
      make it drive a different engine.
    </li>
    <li>
      The path by which Playwright, Puppeteer and Selenium drive a
      <em>non-Chromium</em> browser is BiDi.
    </li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    So BiDi is both the standard and the practical answer. Where the standard has
    no command for something — computed styles, fragment geometry, the tracks a
    grid was given — those live under an <code>otlyra:</code> prefix, which is
    what the specification reserves vendor extensions for.
  </p>

  <h2>The protocol directly</h2>
  <pre><code>$ otlyra --bidi 0
ws://127.0.0.1:52999/session</code></pre>
  <p>
    Port <code>0</code> asks the system for a free one and the browser prints what
    it got, because guessing a port is how two drivers come to fight each other.
    It binds the loopback and nothing else: this endpoint navigates, clicks and
    reads what is on screen, and a port that answered the network would hand all
    of that to whoever asked.
  </p>
  <table>
    <tr><th>Working now</th><th></th></tr>
    <tr><td><code>session.*</code></td><td>status, new, end, subscribe, unsubscribe</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>browsingContext.*</code></td><td>getTree, navigate, reload, captureScreenshot, locateNodes</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>input.performActions</code></td><td>pointer, key and wheel actions, with an element as an origin</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>log.entryAdded</code></td><td>What the browser said, as it says it</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>network.*</code></td><td>Every request, and what came back — with two timings</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>otlyra:*</code></td><td>explain, highlight, frameTimings</td></tr>
  </table>

  <h3>What it cannot do yet</h3>
  <p>
    <code>script.evaluate</code> needs a script engine, and there is not one yet.
    Stock Playwright leans on it for nearly everything, so Playwright will connect
    to this and then fail. The browser answers that command with
    <code>unsupported operation</code> and names the milestone it is waiting on —
    told apart from <code>unknown command</code> deliberately, because a client
    that meets it is looking at a gap with a date on it rather than at a typo.
  </p>

  <h2>A client you can read</h2>
  <p>
    <a href="https://github.com/octofhir/Otlyra/tree/main/examples/bidi">
      <code>examples/bidi/</code>
    </a> holds a complete BiDi client in the Python standard library — no
    <code>pip install</code>, about ninety lines of which most is WebSocket
    framing — and a script that drives the browser the way an agent would. It is
    there to be read: the protocol is JSON in and JSON out, and seeing that is
    worth more than a dependency.
  </p>
  <p>
    For real work, use a real client. Puppeteer and Selenium both speak BiDi and
    handle reconnection, timeouts and events properly.
  </p>
</Base>
